This problem would be more interesting if there were some restrictions on what values of `a[]` are permitted. As it stands now, this can basically be accomplished simply by writing the desired H value as a base-31 integer, with a very slight modification.

To represent every possible int value we need 7 base-31 digits, since 31&lt;sup&gt;6&lt;/sup&gt; &lt; 2&lt;sup&gt;32&lt;/sup&gt; &lt; 31&lt;sup&gt;7&lt;/sup&gt; 

First, consider an equivalent hash function that perhaps better illustrates the base-31 idea:

```java
    public static int hash2(char[] a) {
        int pow31 = 1;
        int h = 0;
        for (int i = a.length - 1; i &gt;= 0; i--) {
            h += a[i] * pow31;
            pow31 *= 31;
        }
        return h + pow31;
    }
```

And now here&#39;s the simple and fast method to compute a pre-image of the hash function.

```java
...
    private static final long POW31_7 = (long) Math.pow(31, 7); // 31**7 fits in a double
    private static final int POW31_7_MOD_2_32 = (int) POW31_7;
...
    public static char[] pre_image(int h) {
        h -= POW31_7_MOD_2_32;
        char[] result = new char[]{0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0};
        int i = result.length - 1;
