Try this one if you are trying to get last id (numeric value)

    SELECT MAX(COLUMN_NAME)
    FROM TABLE_NAME
thats it.

And if you want to get whole data of last row then call `getRowCount()` method and select the record at that reference. check out code example.  
**getRowCount() method:**

    public int getRowCount(String tableName) {
            int count = 0;
            try {
                res = st.executeQuery(&quot;SELECT COUNT(*) FROM &quot; + tableName);
                while (res.next()) {
                    count = res.getInt(1);
                }
            } catch (SQLException ex) {
                ex.printStackTrace();
                JOptionPane.showMessageDialog(null, &quot;Table not found record getting&quot;);
            }
            return count;
        }
It will return an int value so use it as

    SELECT * FROM TABLE_NAME WHERE ID = getRowCount(TABLE_NAME);
And the result is your last record.

You can kickstart your batch job manually like this  

 

    @Component
    Class Someclass{
      ...............
         @Autowired
         private JobLauncher jobLauncher;
         @Autowired
         private Job job;  
        
         public void someFunction(){
           jobLauncher.run(job, new JobParameters());  
       }
    }

Only thing is you cannot restart a batch job if it is already completed, It throws an error saying the status is COMPLETED. For this to work you have to set `allowStartIfComplete` property to true. This has to be done in your batch step configuration,  something like this 

    stepBuilderFactory.get(&quot;step1&quot;)
                    .&lt;Person, Person&gt; chunk(10)
                    .reader(reader())
                    .processor(processor())
                    .writer(writer())
                    .allowStartIfComplete(true)
                    .build();

Run the job with empty parameters:

    jobLauncher.run(job, new JobParameters());

If you already have parameters and they aren&#39;t empty try this work around: 

    JobParameters jobParameters = new JobParametersBuilder()
                .addLong(&quot;id&quot;, 500L)
                .addDate(&quot;startedAt&quot;, new Date())
                .toJobParameters();

    jobLauncher.run(job, jobParameters);

added the current date as parameter

Note: it will be a bit tricky to get execution from `JobRepository` by `JobParameters`

