answers.body_markdown:
As the comment on your post mentions, this is a client side producer error caused by too many open files or file descriptors.

As the producer client does not use any files, most likely this is related to a high number of connections and I would suspect in this case that you are creating too many KafkaProducer objects which will in turn create a connection per object and use a file handle.

One common mistake lambda developers make is to instantiate the producer in the handleRequest method instead of globally and I suspect that is maybe whats happening here or something similar.

To fix, ensure that you only have 1 instance of a producer by creating it globally as a singleton. e.g. 

```
public class MyLambdaHandler implements RequestHandler&lt;String, String&gt; {

    // Define the Kafka producer outside the handler method.
    // Instantiate in the constructor.
    private final KafkaProducer&lt;String, String&gt; kafkaProducer;
```

Alternatively, if you need more than one producer then store in a HashMap or similar but either way add a mechanism to ensure you are not constantly instantiating new objects.

*Update following comment*: To validate the above theory I would recommend adding metrics and logging to measure the client side connection count from the lambda to MSK. If this is your only producer you can use the server side metric.

